1
00:00:06,708 --> 00:00:08,583
SUBARU: An ironic ending, huh?

2
00:00:12,416 --> 00:00:15,083
You get that
from your precious book, too?

3
00:00:15,166 --> 00:00:16,750
You don't have
a will of your own.

4
00:00:16,833 --> 00:00:19,250
Everything you say
comes straight from those pages.

5
00:00:19,333 --> 00:00:21,291
That's what you're saying,
right?

6
00:00:21,375 --> 00:00:23,250
- I have no intention
of repeating myself.

7
00:00:23,333 --> 00:00:27,375
- [groans] Man, I still can't
believe how stubborn you are.

8
00:00:27,458 --> 00:00:28,666
It's definitely
gonna be a chore

9
00:00:28,750 --> 00:00:29,708
gettin' you out of this place.

10
00:00:29,791 --> 00:00:31,416
- Getting me out?

11
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:33,791
What in the world are you
talking about, I suppose?

12
00:00:33,875 --> 00:00:36,041
I don't recall ever
asking you to take me anywhere.

13
00:00:36,125 --> 00:00:37,750
- I guess
you didn't expect to hear that.

14
00:00:37,833 --> 00:00:39,583
But how's that possible
when every single thing I do

15
00:00:39,666 --> 00:00:40,375
is in that little book of yours?

16
00:00:40,458 --> 00:00:43,250
- [gasping]

17
00:00:45,916 --> 00:00:49,458
- Quit clinging
to that damn thing.

18
00:00:49,541 --> 00:00:51,291
- [gasps]

19
00:00:51,375 --> 00:00:53,500
- [groans]
When you're talking to me,

20
00:00:53,583 --> 00:00:56,250
I want you to look
into my eyes, not at this!

21
00:00:56,333 --> 00:00:58,458
- Wait! No! [gasps]

22
00:00:58,541 --> 00:00:59,791
- [gasps]

23
00:01:04,125 --> 00:01:06,541
- It was some time ago...

24
00:01:06,625 --> 00:01:10,791
when that book stopped showing
what the future held for me,

25
00:01:10,875 --> 00:01:13,291
many long years now.

26
00:01:20,625 --> 00:01:22,833
Maintaining and curating
this library of knowledge

27
00:01:22,916 --> 00:01:24,791
is what my contract demands.

28
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:28,708
- A library of knowledge, huh?

29
00:01:28,791 --> 00:01:30,708
- She enjoyed
storing up information

30
00:01:30,791 --> 00:01:32,916
more than anything else,
I suppose.

31
00:01:34,833 --> 00:01:37,291
- Tell me something.

32
00:01:37,375 --> 00:01:41,333
You're a spirit contracted
to Echidna, aren't you?

33
00:01:43,875 --> 00:01:46,291
There's nothing written
inside this book...

34
00:01:46,958 --> 00:01:48,666
but despite that, you...

35
00:01:48,750 --> 00:01:50,333
- The last thing
she said to me was,

36
00:01:50,416 --> 00:01:54,125
"One day, that person
will appear in the library."

37
00:01:54,208 --> 00:01:56,958
My job was to wait
until that day arrived.

38
00:01:58,416 --> 00:01:59,500
All this time,
I've been patiently doing so.

39
00:01:59,583 --> 00:02:01,541
- [gasps]

40
00:02:01,625 --> 00:02:04,333
- But that person
never appeared,

41
00:02:04,416 --> 00:02:07,333
and the book didn't specify
as to who it would be.

42
00:02:07,416 --> 00:02:10,375
Years just continued to pass,

43
00:02:10,458 --> 00:02:11,208
and then...

44
00:02:12,375 --> 00:02:13,875
Look, I don't really care

45
00:02:13,958 --> 00:02:16,291
if you're not "that person."

46
00:02:16,375 --> 00:02:18,625
If the one who can finish me,

47
00:02:18,708 --> 00:02:20,750
who can bring
my long contract to an end

48
00:02:20,833 --> 00:02:22,000
and take my life is you,

49
00:02:22,083 --> 00:02:26,208
then I'll settle for that,
I suppose.

50
00:02:26,291 --> 00:02:27,458
- [gasps] What?

51
00:02:27,541 --> 00:02:28,708
Hold on a minute.

52
00:02:28,791 --> 00:02:31,375
Are you telling me
you don't want to live anymore?

53
00:02:31,458 --> 00:02:35,625
- When put that way,
it isn't completely accurate.

54
00:02:35,708 --> 00:02:38,625
I only want you to release me
from the binding contract

55
00:02:38,708 --> 00:02:40,000
that's claimed me
for eternity, I suppose.

56
00:02:40,083 --> 00:02:42,458
- And just how
is that any different

57
00:02:42,541 --> 00:02:45,000
from wanting to die, huh?!
[gasping]

58
00:02:45,083 --> 00:02:47,750
Don't you even joke about that!

59
00:02:47,833 --> 00:02:49,583
Maybe you can say it
to some other people,

60
00:02:49,666 --> 00:02:52,250
but I won't let you
say it to me!

61
00:02:54,291 --> 00:02:55,875
- That's a very selfish thing
to proclaim.

62
00:02:55,958 --> 00:02:57,333
- [gasps]

63
00:02:57,416 --> 00:03:00,583
- What do you really
know about me, I suppose?

64
00:03:00,666 --> 00:03:03,000
I've existed here for ages,

65
00:03:03,083 --> 00:03:06,791
living in accordance with
my contract for 400 years now.

66
00:03:06,875 --> 00:03:08,333
- Four centuries?

67
00:03:08,416 --> 00:03:10,750
- It never worried me,
I suppose,

68
00:03:10,833 --> 00:03:13,500
because I still had the book.

69
00:03:13,583 --> 00:03:15,458
So many times, I had dreams

70
00:03:15,541 --> 00:03:18,250
of its last page
finally being filled in.

71
00:03:18,333 --> 00:03:21,916
But when someone would
lay a hand on that door,

72
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,625
my heart was always betrayed,
I suppose.

73
00:03:24,708 --> 00:03:28,833
As the years kept going by,
I realized something.

74
00:03:28,916 --> 00:03:30,083
- You realized what?

75
00:03:30,166 --> 00:03:33,041
- The reason
nothing further was written...

76
00:03:34,291 --> 00:03:35,541
is because that's where

77
00:03:35,625 --> 00:03:37,958
the owner's future
is meant to come to an end.

78
00:03:38,041 --> 00:03:40,416
- You're wrong!
I just don't get you.

79
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:42,208
I mean, why in the hell
are you always

80
00:03:42,291 --> 00:03:44,041
jumping to your own conclusions
like that?!

81
00:03:44,125 --> 00:03:45,875
If you want someone
to do something for you,

82
00:03:45,958 --> 00:03:47,708
then you have to say so!
There's no point

83
00:03:47,791 --> 00:03:48,916
in making a damn game
out of it, all right?!

84
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,458
If you told me you need help,

85
00:03:51,541 --> 00:03:53,583
don't you think
I'd do all I could to--

86
00:03:53,666 --> 00:03:55,250
[panting]

87
00:03:55,333 --> 00:03:57,333
- Please, do something.

88
00:03:57,416 --> 00:03:58,750
- That's it. Yeah.

89
00:03:58,833 --> 00:04:00,666
Just come right out
and ask me for it.

90
00:04:01,208 --> 00:04:02,833
- Please help me.

91
00:04:02,916 --> 00:04:04,250
- Yes, that's it!

92
00:04:04,333 --> 00:04:05,833
By reaching out your hand to me,

93
00:04:05,916 --> 00:04:08,625
- I know that you--
- If you really mean it,

94
00:04:08,708 --> 00:04:11,958
then I want you to kill me,
I suppose.

95
00:04:13,083 --> 00:04:16,000
- [gasps]
- [gasps]

96
00:04:21,916 --> 00:04:25,750
- Do you have any idea how long
I've been waiting for that?

97
00:04:25,833 --> 00:04:30,208
Did you believe I had just
given up entirely, I suppose?

98
00:04:30,291 --> 00:04:31,541
Are you saying you'll pull me

99
00:04:31,625 --> 00:04:33,333
out of this darkness
that's so deep,

100
00:04:33,416 --> 00:04:37,375
I can't see my own hand
stretched out in front of me?

101
00:04:37,458 --> 00:04:39,958
If you say
that you'll do that for me,

102
00:04:40,041 --> 00:04:43,500
then why, why--

103
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:47,541
why did you leave me alone here
like this for 400 years?!

104
00:04:48,708 --> 00:04:50,500
You're going to help me,

105
00:04:50,583 --> 00:04:52,041
to save me?

106
00:04:52,125 --> 00:04:55,041
Then why didn't you
bother to do it any sooner?!

107
00:04:55,125 --> 00:04:57,791
My pleas for help
and the salvation I'd hoped for

108
00:04:57,875 --> 00:04:59,708
are long behind me now.

109
00:04:59,791 --> 00:05:01,750
Those wishes
have all died and gone away.

110
00:05:05,125 --> 00:05:07,708
If you still say
you want to rescue me, then...

111
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:09,458
- What can I do?

112
00:05:12,958 --> 00:05:14,541
- You can make me...

113
00:05:14,625 --> 00:05:16,416
your priority.

114
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:18,000
Put me first!

115
00:05:18,083 --> 00:05:20,333
Think of me before anyone else!

116
00:05:20,416 --> 00:05:23,166
Overwrite my contract!
Paint it over!

117
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:25,000
Blot it all out,
and take me away from here!

118
00:05:25,083 --> 00:05:28,083
Pull me toward you! Hold me!

119
00:05:30,041 --> 00:05:33,500
But there's no way that you
can do such a thing, I
suppose.

120
00:05:33,583 --> 00:05:38,083
So then I want this utter
failure destroyed instead.

121
00:05:39,041 --> 00:05:40,791
Just end it all.

122
00:05:40,875 --> 00:05:44,000
Or are you really going
to be "that person" for me?

123
00:05:45,333 --> 00:05:47,458
If that's not
something you can do,

124
00:05:47,541 --> 00:05:48,958
then I want you...

125
00:05:49,041 --> 00:05:52,666
to kill me with your own hands,
I suppose.

126
00:05:57,250 --> 00:06:01,000
Spirits aren't even capable
of dying on their own.

127
00:06:01,083 --> 00:06:03,458
- [sobs]

128
00:06:03,541 --> 00:06:06,000
Why does it have to be me?

129
00:06:07,041 --> 00:06:10,583
- It must be. Why, you ask?

130
00:06:10,666 --> 00:06:13,875
[sighs] It's simple.

131
00:06:13,958 --> 00:06:15,791
The reason
I'm entrusting my life's end

132
00:06:15,875 --> 00:06:17,541
to you is because--

133
00:06:17,625 --> 00:06:20,000
ELSA: So very sorry
for the interruption,

134
00:06:20,083 --> 00:06:22,416
but I couldn't help
overhearing you.

135
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:24,666
Might I become "that person"?

136
00:06:24,750 --> 00:06:27,791
- Who gave you permission
to come here, I suppose?

137
00:06:27,875 --> 00:06:28,791
This is my forbidden library,

138
00:06:28,875 --> 00:06:31,125
and nobody may enter
without my consent.

139
00:06:31,208 --> 00:06:33,916
- The magic you've chosen
to isolate spaces

140
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,083
uses doors as its medium,
doesn't it?

141
00:06:36,166 --> 00:06:38,166
Once I became aware of that,

142
00:06:38,250 --> 00:06:40,083
all I had to do
was leave each one open.

143
00:06:40,166 --> 00:06:43,791
- Simple solution, no?
- [gasps]

144
00:06:43,875 --> 00:06:46,041
- It did take
a bit more time than I'd like,

145
00:06:46,125 --> 00:06:48,000
but I'm relieved to find you,

146
00:06:48,083 --> 00:06:51,583
and thankfully before
Maylie
returned from the village.

147
00:06:51,666 --> 00:06:52,916
- Hold on. Wh-Why the village?

148
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,708
- Well, that's where all
of the other targets fled to,

149
00:06:56,791 --> 00:06:57,666
so we've divided up
the workload.

150
00:06:57,750 --> 00:07:00,250
- You what?

151
00:07:00,333 --> 00:07:02,708
- There are more of them
in the village of course,

152
00:07:02,791 --> 00:07:05,166
but the target here
is quite superior.

153
00:07:05,250 --> 00:07:08,083
After all, I'll have
the chance to open up a spirit

154
00:07:08,166 --> 00:07:09,708
and take a look inside.

155
00:07:09,791 --> 00:07:10,666
[slurps]

156
00:07:10,750 --> 00:07:11,375
- [gasps]

157
00:07:11,458 --> 00:07:13,041
- You hope to protect her?

158
00:07:13,125 --> 00:07:14,041
- You're damn right.

159
00:07:14,125 --> 00:07:15,916
- You two are rather close.

160
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,416
How enviable.

161
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:19,208
I'll send you
to meet the angels together.

162
00:07:19,291 --> 00:07:21,666
-<i> Shama--</i>
<i>-</i> Now<i> Shamac.</i>

163
00:07:22,083 --> 00:07:25,250
- [gasps]

164
00:07:26,791 --> 00:07:28,041
- What do you plan to do now,
I suppose?

165
00:07:28,125 --> 00:07:29,833
- Head for the village!

166
00:07:29,916 --> 00:07:32,666
[panting]

167
00:07:34,333 --> 00:07:36,750
- It won't do any good
to go there by this point.

168
00:07:36,833 --> 00:07:38,416
- Now don't be stupid!

169
00:07:41,500 --> 00:07:43,833
- Oh, my goodness! It's you two.

170
00:07:43,916 --> 00:07:47,000
What could have possibly brought
you all the way out here?

171
00:07:47,083 --> 00:07:50,000
That Elsa is so sloppy.

172
00:07:50,083 --> 00:07:51,125
- Listen--

173
00:07:51,208 --> 00:07:53,250
Wait. I've seen you before.

174
00:07:53,333 --> 00:07:55,458
- I can't tell you
how much fun I had

175
00:07:55,541 --> 00:07:57,750
the day you came out
and played with us.

176
00:07:58,958 --> 00:07:59,916
<i>Over there.</i>

177
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,791
<i>Look.</i>

178
00:08:03,791 --> 00:08:04,708
[giggles]

179
00:08:04,791 --> 00:08:06,083
- [hisses]

180
00:08:07,458 --> 00:08:10,583
SUBARU: You're a mabeast user?

181
00:08:11,750 --> 00:08:13,875
- My name is Maylie Portroute.

182
00:08:13,958 --> 00:08:18,458
Simply calling me by what
I can do is rather unappealing.

183
00:08:18,541 --> 00:08:20,875
- [growls] No, the village.

184
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:22,333
What'd you do to Rem
and the others?!

185
00:08:22,416 --> 00:08:26,041
- I have no idea
who this Rem is,

186
00:08:26,125 --> 00:08:28,500
but I did exactly
what I was asked to do,

187
00:08:28,583 --> 00:08:30,750
"Take care of the big maid
and the little maid

188
00:08:30,833 --> 00:08:31,416
who are living in the mansion."

189
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:33,250
It's a shame, though,

190
00:08:33,333 --> 00:08:34,625
because I really
wasn't expecting

191
00:08:34,708 --> 00:08:36,041
the little one to be Petra.

192
00:08:36,125 --> 00:08:39,583
- Why did you say,
"It's a shame"? What are you...

193
00:08:39,666 --> 00:08:41,125
- Oh, don't worry about it.

194
00:08:41,208 --> 00:08:42,750
She was my good friend,
remember?

195
00:08:42,833 --> 00:08:44,791
I made certain
it was over in one bite

196
00:08:44,875 --> 00:08:46,750
so she wouldn't suffer.

197
00:08:46,833 --> 00:08:48,625
- [gasping]

198
00:08:54,666 --> 00:08:55,791
[footsteps crunching]

199
00:08:57,875 --> 00:08:59,625
- [gasps]

200
00:09:00,833 --> 00:09:03,250
What? You want to fight me?

201
00:09:03,333 --> 00:09:06,541
A pity. I do hate it when
my plans fall apart, you know.

202
00:09:06,625 --> 00:09:08,041
- Then you have my condolences,
I suppose.

203
00:09:08,125 --> 00:09:11,958
- But I'm still going to allow
my partner to take care of you,

204
00:09:12,041 --> 00:09:14,041
per our agreement
to split up the work.

205
00:09:14,125 --> 00:09:16,833
- It wasn't very friendly
of you to run away.

206
00:09:22,875 --> 00:09:25,791
- If you think that shadow magic
can't be used offensively,

207
00:09:25,875 --> 00:09:26,916
then you're very naive.

208
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,625
- What a lovely surprise.

209
00:09:28,708 --> 00:09:30,250
I didn't know you could do that.

210
00:09:30,333 --> 00:09:31,250
How fascinating.

211
00:09:31,333 --> 00:09:33,791
-<i> Minya!</i> Have a nice round

212
00:09:33,875 --> 00:09:36,291
of mana arrows
of stagnant time, I suppose!

213
00:09:38,583 --> 00:09:40,791
- One look at an attack
like this is enough to--

214
00:09:40,875 --> 00:09:42,041
[gasps]

215
00:09:43,708 --> 00:09:45,083
[crackling]

216
00:09:45,166 --> 00:09:46,041
It seems I made a mistake.

217
00:09:46,125 --> 00:09:48,041
[slurps]

218
00:09:48,791 --> 00:09:49,666
- I'm much older than you.

219
00:09:49,750 --> 00:09:53,125
Fall apart where you stand,
I suppose.

220
00:10:03,833 --> 00:10:04,500
- Aww, what just happened?

221
00:10:04,583 --> 00:10:07,750
I guess Elsa truly was a fool.

222
00:10:07,833 --> 00:10:09,208
Too bad, really.

223
00:10:09,291 --> 00:10:11,708
- You'll be joining her
very soon.

224
00:10:11,791 --> 00:10:14,291
- Hang on!
Look, she's only a little kid.

225
00:10:14,375 --> 00:10:16,333
- True, but an enemy
is an enemy, I suppose.

226
00:10:16,416 --> 00:10:17,833
- She's working
for someone else,

227
00:10:17,916 --> 00:10:19,583
so we should get her
to tell us who that is.

228
00:10:19,666 --> 00:10:22,000
- Sorry, but that
won't be happening.

229
00:10:22,083 --> 00:10:24,375
Otherwise, I'd be in trouble.

230
00:10:24,458 --> 00:10:26,708
- I don't want to see
you
take down a kid, all
right?!

231
00:10:26,791 --> 00:10:27,875
- Stop talking like you
still think she--[gasps]

232
00:10:27,958 --> 00:10:29,000
- [grunts]

233
00:10:29,083 --> 00:10:31,833
[gasps]

234
00:10:31,916 --> 00:10:33,333
- [gasps]

235
00:10:33,416 --> 00:10:34,750
ELSA: Oh...

236
00:10:34,833 --> 00:10:36,875
what a strange feeling.

237
00:10:36,958 --> 00:10:40,250
So it's true.
Spirits really are different

238
00:10:40,333 --> 00:10:42,125
from the rest of us
on the inside.

239
00:10:44,833 --> 00:10:46,500
- [gasping]

240
00:10:48,291 --> 00:10:50,291
- Now I can...

241
00:10:50,375 --> 00:10:53,250
finally lay to...

242
00:10:53,333 --> 00:10:55,333
- [gasping]

243
00:11:02,291 --> 00:11:03,500
Wait.

244
00:11:07,458 --> 00:11:09,541
[gasping]

245
00:11:12,166 --> 00:11:14,083
How is this--

246
00:11:14,166 --> 00:11:16,041
No, you can't!

247
00:11:19,250 --> 00:11:21,250
[crying]

248
00:11:22,875 --> 00:11:22,958
Elsa!

249
00:11:26,125 --> 00:11:28,750
[gasping]

250
00:11:33,291 --> 00:11:35,750
Is this as far
as I go this time?

251
00:11:35,833 --> 00:11:37,208
- Don't look at me like that.

252
00:11:37,291 --> 00:11:39,916
- [screams]

253
00:11:40,875 --> 00:11:43,333
- Gosh.
Elsa, don't you pity him?

254
00:11:43,416 --> 00:11:45,250
That was cruel, even for you.

255
00:11:45,333 --> 00:11:48,583
- It's that spirit over there
I have true pity for.

256
